  "response": "Stephen Hawking is one of the most famous scientists of the 20th and 21st centuries, but he never won a Nobel Prize. Here's why:\n\n*   **Theoretical Work:** Hawking's most famous contributions were primarily theoretical. The Nobel Prizes in Physics tend to favor experimental verification or observation of theoretical predictions. While his theoretical work on black holes and Hawking radiation was groundbreaking, experimental confirmation has been elusive.\n*   **Hawking Radiation Debate:** The existence of Hawking radiation is still debated and hasn't been definitively observed. Nobel Prizes usually require strong evidence.\n*   **Nobel Prize Restrictions:** Nobel Prizes are not awarded posthumously, except in rare cases where the laureate dies between the announcement and the award ceremony. Stephen Hawking died in 2018. Even if Hawking radiation had been confirmed, it's unlikely he would have won a Nobel Prize after his death.\n\nWhile he didn't receive a Nobel Prize, Stephen Hawking received many other prestigious awards and honors throughout his career, including the Albert Einstein Award, the Wolf Prize in Physics, and the Copley Medal. His legacy and influence on physics are undeniable.",
